inlineContent.text: Apps that support a complication must define a class that supports the

protocol and register it with the system. Your data source is responsible for providing timeline entries and data for all of the complication families that you support. You do this by implementing the protocol methods, returning the timeline entries displayed by your complication and information about the features that your complication supports.

You don’t instantiate your data source class explicitly. After defining your class, specify the class name in the General tab of the project settings for your WatchKit extension. When the system needs data, ClockKit instantiates your data source and initializes it by calling its
method. Once initialized, ClockKit calls the corresponding protocol methods to gather any needed data. You can also specify your class name in your app’s
When the user installs your complication on the clock face, ClockKit creates an appropriate

object for the selected complication family. ClockKit then passes the complication to your data source so that you know how to format your timeline entries. Use the General tab of your WatchKit extension’s project settings to specify the families you support.

to specify whether your app can batch load future timeline entries.
ClockKit calls your data source methods on your watchOS app’s main thread.
